569
00:23:01,795 --> 00:23:04,170
If it didn't download a file
to your computer, try again.

570
00:23:04,170 --> 00:23:05,870
Make sure it downloads
it appropriately.

571
00:23:05,870 --> 00:23:09,620
And again, in the future, I
don't have to necessarily create

572
00:23:09,620 --> 00:23:10,140
a new one.

573
00:23:10,140 --> 00:23:11,598
I can just say,
OK, let's come here

574
00:23:11,598 --> 00:23:13,223
and select Sharad's
MacBook Pro, or you

575
00:23:13,223 --> 00:23:14,723
can see there's a
bunch of past ones

576
00:23:14,723 --> 00:23:16,260
that we have in
there as well, too.

577
00:23:16,260 --> 00:23:19,173
There's nothing secret about
the name of the key pair itself.

578
00:23:19,173 --> 00:23:20,840
The only important
thing to keep private

579
00:23:20,840 --> 00:23:22,568
is that private key file.

580
00:23:22,568 --> 00:23:24,110
If somebody gets
access to that, they

581
00:23:24,110 --> 00:23:26,220
can access your remote instance.

582
00:23:26,220 --> 00:23:29,490
So keep that in mind, assuming
that I always have the IP

583
00:23:29,490 --> 00:23:31,800
address and other stuff.

584
00:23:31,800 --> 00:23:33,720
We got the key pair set up.

585
00:23:33,720 --> 00:23:36,942
Then coming in here, we
have the network settings.

586
00:23:36,942 --> 00:23:38,400
For what we're
doing here, we don't

587
00:23:38,400 --> 00:23:41,530
have to worry about the
actual network we're using.

588
00:23:41,530 --> 00:23:43,650
Though, conceivably,
you can do some things

589
00:23:43,650 --> 00:23:45,375
like leveraging
virtual private clouds,

590
00:23:45,375 --> 00:23:47,250
where we basically create
an isolated portion

591
00:23:47,250 --> 00:23:48,960
of the cloud for maybe our
organization or something

592
00:23:48,960 --> 00:23:49,690
like that.

593
00:23:49,690 --> 00:23:52,602
But for what we're doing, we
won't worry about those pieces.

594
00:23:52,602 --> 00:23:55,060
The most important part for us
is actually right down here,

595
00:23:55,060 --> 00:23:56,740
when we get to the
