596
00:23:56,740 --> 00:24:00,750
This basically says or
establishes what sort of traffic

597
00:24:00,750 --> 00:24:04,320
is allowed in and
out of the instance.

598
00:24:04,320 --> 00:24:07,170
This may be not something we--
or this might not be something

599
00:24:07,170 --> 00:24:08,260
you often think about.

600
00:24:08,260 --> 00:24:11,040
But basically, when we are
making a connection, when

601
00:24:11,040 --> 00:24:13,200
I'm going to a
website, that website

602
00:24:13,200 --> 00:24:16,930
has an IP address, a unique
address associated with it.

603
00:24:16,930 --> 00:24:17,860
It'll look like this.

604
00:24:17,860 --> 00:24:20,318
It'll be some number dot, some
number dot, some number dot,

605
00:24:20,318 --> 00:24:22,100
some number,
something like that.

606
00:24:22,100 --> 00:24:24,690
To make that
connection, we basically

607
00:24:24,690 --> 00:24:27,970
have to use our computer
on our home network.

608
00:24:27,970 --> 00:24:31,170
We have to allow our--
home internet network has

609
00:24:31,170 --> 00:24:34,060
to allow traffic to go
out from our computer,

610
00:24:34,060 --> 00:24:37,810
out of our home, to whatever
the remote server is.

611
00:24:37,810 --> 00:24:42,790
That remote server has to allow
any IP address to come into it,

612
00:24:42,790 --> 00:24:44,400
retrieve information,
and then it

613
00:24:44,400 --> 00:24:46,660
has to also allow the
information to go back out.

614
00:24:46,660 --> 00:24:49,860
And then our home network
has to allow information

615
00:24:49,860 --> 00:24:52,620
to come back into, but
very specific Information

616
00:24:52,620 --> 00:24:53,730
we requested.

617
00:24:53,730 --> 00:24:56,200
This sort of handoff
happens behind the scenes

618
00:24:56,200 --> 00:24:58,870
so quickly and completely,
imperceptibly to us.

619
00:24:58,870 --> 00:25:00,460
But now that we're
setting this up,

620
00:25:00,460 --> 00:25:02,530
we want to have fine-tuned
control over this

621
00:25:02,530 --> 00:25:04,810
so we can allow only certain
information in and out.

622
00:25:04,810 --> 00:25:07,480
It's another layer of security
to basically say, well--

623
00:25:07,480 --> 00:25:10,090
for example, if I don't
check these two boxes,

624
00:25:10,090 --> 00:25:13,720
allow HTTPS traffic
and allow HTTP traffic.

625
00:25:13,720 --> 00:25:18,900
Then if somebody tries to come
to my IP address via a website

626
00:25:18,900 --> 00:25:22,368
approach using HTTP, it just
won't allow it in and be

627
00:25:22,368 --> 00:25:23,660
like, well, that's not allowed.

628
00:25:23,660 --> 00:25:26,890
I only allow things that are
coming in as SSH traffic, which

629
00:25:26,890 --> 00:25:29,440
is how we're actually going
to connect to this instance.

630
00:25:29,440 --> 00:25:33,200
So this is another kind of layer
of security we can add on to it.

631
00:25:33,200 --> 00:25:35,950
Similar to the key pair,
I can select existing ones

632
00:25:35,950 --> 00:25:37,630
once I've created them.

633
00:25:37,630 --> 00:25:39,610
So I can create a very
specific one, the name,

634
00:25:39,610 --> 00:25:41,652
and say like, hey, this
is all of my rules in it.

635
00:25:41,652 --> 00:25:44,353
And we'll use these rules
throughout the semester

636
00:25:44,353 --> 00:25:45,770
so you'll see what
I mean by that.

637
00:25:45,770 --> 00:25:50,920
But for now, we're only going
to allow SSH traffic in.

638
00:25:50,920 --> 00:25:53,710
And specifically, we're going
to allow it from anywhere.

639
00:25:53,710 --> 00:25:56,680
What that means is it
says, OK, well-- so SSH

640
00:25:56,680 --> 00:25:58,780
is a secure shell protocol.

641
00:25:58,780 --> 00:26:01,300
And it says, I'm
allowing you to--

642
00:26:01,300 --> 00:26:03,618
you'll see, we'll do
it from the terminal

643
00:26:03,618 --> 00:26:04,660
or from the command line.

644
00:26:04,660 --> 00:26:09,910
And we'll say, I'm allowing
you to use this protocol

645
00:26:09,910 --> 00:26:12,370
to connect to this EC2 instance.

646
00:26:12,370 --> 00:26:17,780
And I'm allowing you to do
that from any IP address.

647
00:26:17,780 --> 00:26:20,422
That is technically not the
most secure way to do it.

648
00:26:20,422 --> 00:26:22,880
If I wanted to be very secure,
I could say, well, actually,

649
00:26:22,880 --> 00:26:26,800
I'm going to only allow SSH
traffic from my home IP address.

650
00:26:26,800 --> 00:26:29,910
That way, if somebody tries
to connect to my EC2 instance,

651
00:26:29,910 --> 00:26:33,080
even if they have my private key
pair, unless they're on my home

652
00:26:33,080 --> 00:26:34,760
network, they can't get in.

653
00:26:34,760 --> 00:26:36,180
They can't connect to it.

654
00:26:36,180 --> 00:26:38,900
So if I'm a company or an
organization, what I might do

655
00:26:38,900 --> 00:26:41,630
is I might say, OK, well,
this range of IP addresses

656
00:26:41,630 --> 00:26:43,320
is associated with our office.

657
00:26:43,320 --> 00:26:46,980
If you're not within our office
or not VPN into our office,

658
00:26:46,980 --> 00:26:50,060
you cannot access this network,
or you cannot access this EC2

659
00:26:50,060 --> 00:26:51,440
instance.

660
00:26:51,440 --> 00:26:55,010
So that is one way to create
another layer of security

661
00:26:55,010 --> 00:26:57,750
around your EC2 instance here.

662
00:26:57,750 --> 00:27:00,030
Also, if I'm ever using
terms that don't make sense,

